The DA’s John Steenhuisen said the government has failed to provide a rational, fact-based justification for an extended national lockdown. JOHANNESBURG - The DA is going to court to force the government to make public all the minutes of National Command Council meetings, including the one where the decision to ban tobacco sales was made. The party's interim leader John Steenhuisen says there's absolutely no reason for South Africa to continue being under lockdown. READ: NCC reports on challenges, successes of COVID-19 strategies He said the government has failed to provide a rational, fact-based justification for an extended national lockdown. "They cannot show us the modelling they use, when to tighten, when to ease," said Steenhuisen. READ: Ramaphosa part of decision to ban sale of tobacco products "They don't seem to know for sure, and so every decision is now shrouded in secrecy. We have to blindly trust a body called the National Command Council, a small group of ministers who don't account to Parliament or anyone else. "We asked for meeting minutes to clarify how they backtracked on a decision to ban cigarettes, and they claimed this was classified information." READ: SA Lockdown: Political leaders welcome COVID-19 measures  Meanwhile, Finance Minister Tito Mboweni lambasted the DA for its view on the lockdown. READ: South Africa enters into level 4 lockdown He said Steenhuisen has no right to instruct the president. Mboweni says Steenhuisen must stay in his lane. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.